User Guide - Uploading Documents to the Source Library

Welcome 👋

This guide explains how to correctly upload documents so they can be processed and used by the Copilot assistant.

Following these steps ensures:

Accurate answers from the assistant

Faster processing

Less need for manual fixes



---

1. Folder Structure (Very Important)

Each document must be placed in the correct category folder.

Rules:

Only one folder level deep

Each folder represents a category

Do not create folders inside folders


Example:

RawPolicies/
  HR/
  IT/
  Finance/

Good:

HR/Annual Leave Policy.pdf


Not allowed:

HR/Leave/Annual Leave Policy.pdf

Files directly in the root (no folder)



---

2. Required Metadata

After uploading a file, you must complete both columns:

Status (Required)

Choose one:

Draft → Not ready yet

Approved → Ready to be used by the assistant

Archived → No longer valid


👉 Only Approved documents are used.


---

Document Type (Required)

Choose one:

FAQ

Policy

Procedure

Guidance

Form


👉 Pick the closest match — don’t overthink it.


---

3. Accepted File Types

Use these formats only:

PDF (.pdf) ✅ Preferred

Word (.docx)

Text (.txt)


Avoid:

Images (.png, .jpg)

PowerPoint (.pptx)

Excel (.xlsx)


👉 These formats don’t convert well into usable knowledge.


---

4. What Makes a “Good” Document

The assistant works best with clean, text-based content.

Best quality documents:

Text-based PDFs (exported from Word)

Minimal images

Clear headings and structure

Consistent formatting



---

Avoid if possible:

Scanned PDFs (photos of documents)

Documents with lots of images or diagrams

Poorly formatted or messy layouts

Screenshots pasted into documents


👉 If you can highlight text in the PDF, it’s good. 👉 If you can’t, it likely needs OCR and may perform poorly.


---

5. Quick Upload Checklist ✅

Before you finish:

[ ] File is in the correct folder

[ ] Status is set

[ ] Document Type is set

[ ] Document is text-based (not scanned)



---

6. Common Mistakes to Avoid

Uploading files without setting metadata

Creating extra folder levels

Using inconsistent categories

Leaving documents as Draft when they should be Approved



---

7. Final Tip

Keep it simple.

If a document is:

In the right folder

Marked as Approved

Clearly written


…it will work well in the assistant.

If not — it won’t. Simple as that 
